# Security Rules — MUST follow at all times

CursorBlame executes `git` as a child process and opens URLs in the user's browser.
These are attack surfaces. The following rules are **non-negotiable**.

## 1. No shell execution — use `execFile()` only

- ALL git invocations MUST use Node's `child_process.execFile()` with an **explicit argument array**.
- NEVER use `exec()`, `execSync()`, template-string command assembly, or `shell: true`.
- This prevents command injection through file paths, branch names, or remote URLs.

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT — arguments are never interpolated into a shell string
execFile("git", ["blame", "--line-porcelain", "--", filePath], { cwd }, callback);

// ❌ FORBIDDEN — shell interpolation allows injection
exec(`git blame --line-porcelain -- "${filePath}"`, callback);
```

## 2. SHA validation before URL embedding

- Commit SHAs MUST be validated with `/^[0-9a-f]{40}$/` before being embedded in any URL.
- Use the existing `isValidSha()` helper in [gitBlame.ts](mdc:src/gitBlame.ts).
- NEVER concatenate an unvalidated SHA into a URL string.

## 3. HTTPS-only URLs

- `remoteUrl.ts` normalises SSH and `git://` remotes to `https://` before returning them.
- ALL URLs returned from `commitUrl()` or `buildCommitUrl()` MUST use the `https://` scheme.
- The `isSafeUrl()` guard in [extension.ts](mdc:src/extension.ts) MUST be called before passing any URL to `vscode.env.openExternal()`.
- NEVER open `http://`, `file://`, `javascript:`, or any other scheme.

## 4. `--` separator in git commands

- When passing file paths to git commands, always use `"--"` before the path to prevent path-as-option injection (e.g. a file named `--output`).

## 5. Workspace trust

- The extension MUST remain disabled in untrusted workspaces.
- The `activate()` function checks `vscode.workspace.isTrusted` and defers `doActivate()` until trust is granted.
- NEVER bypass or weaken this check.

## 6. No secrets or credentials

- Do NOT store, log, or transmit authentication tokens, passwords, or API keys.
- The extension is read-only — it only reads git history; it never writes or pushes.

## 7. Input sanitisation in Markdown

- All user-controlled strings rendered in `MarkdownString` (hover tooltips) MUST be escaped with `escapeMd()` in [decoration.ts](mdc:src/decoration.ts).
- This prevents Markdown-injection that could produce misleading command-links.

## 8. Command argument validation

- When the `openCommit` command receives arguments via URI-encoded command-links, they are JSON-parsed and validated.
- NEVER trust command arguments blindly — always type-check and validate before use.

## 9. Security comments must not echo forbidden patterns

- When writing comments or doc-strings that explain why `exec()` or `shell: true` are forbidden, **do NOT reproduce the literal strings** `exec(` or `shell: true` in the comment text.
- Use paraphrases instead, e.g. *"the shell option is never enabled"* rather than `shell: true is never used`.
- Reason: the CI security grep scans all `.ts` source lines for these patterns. Even though the grep filters out comment lines (lines whose content starts with `//` or `*`), writing the literal forbidden string in comments is fragile and confusing.

## Summary checklist for every PR

- [ ] No `exec()` or `shell: true` anywhere in **code** (comments may not echo these literals either — see rule 9)
- [ ] SHAs validated before URL construction
- [ ] Only `https://` URLs returned or opened
- [ ] `--` separates options from paths in all git commands
- [ ] Workspace trust gate intact
- [ ] User strings escaped in Markdown output
